{"key":"processedPost-12384279","value":{"id":12384279,"first":12377916,"last":12384380,"when":1271174085,"utime":"04/13/10 06:54 PM","content":"Adding a casing layer to half a substrate and leaving the other half uncased is like taking both wheels off the passenger side of a car to see if the wheeled side works better than the unwheeled side.<br /><br />The only legitimate way to experiment with this is to case ten to twenty substrates, and leave ten to twenty uncased.&nbsp; Then compare yields and performance, averaged over the whole lot.&nbsp; I've done this many times and is the reason I started saying a few years ago that a casing layer is of little to no benefit to cubensis growing on bulk substrates.<br /><br />The fact is, cubensis isn't among the species that require a casing layer.&nbsp; Other species such as agaricus(button mushrooms) won't fruit in captivity without one.<br />RR","title":"Re: half and half","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}